\section{Related Work and Future Directions}
\label{sec:related}

\noindent
\textbf{Related automation tools.} 
Strong integration with external provers has long been a key advantage in Isabelle/HOL~\cite{sledgehammersmt}. \sledgehammer{} proved essential to our approach. In other theorem provers (e.g.\ Coq, Lean, Agda), analogous combinations with SMT or resolution provers are less mature but still possible. Our \supersketch{} approach can in principle be adapted to any environment where subgoals can be automatically discharged by a solver or tactic. 

Specialized multi-step tactics like \texttt{tryhard}~\cite{tryhard} in Isabelle or controlled automation in HOL4~\cite{ControlledAutomation} also aim to reduce user overhead. Our scenario differs in the sheer scale of subgoals, requiring concurrency, robust fallback splits, and integrated sub-proof generation. Eisbach~\cite{Eisbach} offers a powerful language for building custom proof methods in Isabelle, which can reduce script size; combining Eisbach with \supersketch{} might further streamline large proofs.

Proof repair has also been explored in Coq, notably the “Pumpkin Patch” approach~\cite{coqpumpkin}. Our \superfix{} differs in that it is purely external at the Isabelle/ML layer, interacting with top-level transitions, rather than modifying internal proof terms. This design suits Isabelle’s LCF approach but might be adapted to other systems. Eunsuk Kang and Mark Aagaard’s “Controlled Automation Tactics” for HOL~\cite{KangAagaard2007} address usability in a more prescriptive style, whereas \superfix{} focuses on post-hoc script repair.

\smallskip
\noindent
\textbf{Exporting or generalising.} 
One may wonder if off-the-shelf model checkers or IC3-based tools~\cite{IC3} could do the heavy lifting for our 2-device, 1-location model. In principle, yes—but we aim ultimately to scale to more devices and more addresses, and to prove deeper memory-model properties. We therefore prefer an ITP approach that supports modular expansions and is easily integrated with other theorems about concurrency or memory consistency. Tools like Murphi~\cite{Murphi} or Ivy~\cite{IVy} can check smaller protocol instances but do not provide the same high-assurance environment as Isabelle/HOL. In the future, we may combine them for quicker bug-hunting before final theorem proving.

\smallskip
\noindent
\textbf{Future work.}
We see several ways to further improve \(\supersketch\) and \(\superfix\). One is auto-deriving splitting tactics from the structure of goals, so we do not have to specify them manually. Another is better management of concurrency (e.g.\ using a global scheduler) to systematically avoid or fix \sledgehammer{} “bad proofs.” We also hope to integrate \(\superfix\) with more advanced hint-based proof repair, potentially inspired by Pumpkin Patch~\cite{coqpumpkin}.

Regarding the \CXLcache{} model, we plan to refine it to more devices and addresses, aiming at verifying not just coherence but also consistency-litmus-test scenarios. We can exploit the existing partial proofs, with \(\supersketch\) and \(\superfix\) automating a large fraction of re-proving. Ultimately, we envision a single “push-button” approach to re-check or fix the entire proof after updates, though this requires deeper integration with Isabelle’s internal scheduling. We also plan to improve third-party infrastructure (e.g.\ DeepIsaHOL) so that others can reproduce or extend our approach in general-purpose large proofs.

\section{Conclusion}

Our experience in proving the \(\SWMR\) property for a formal model of \CXLcache{} highlights the heavy proof-engineering overhead in large-scale mechanised proofs. Off-the-shelf automation was not enough to handle 50k+ subgoals that shifted each time we revised the invariant or the model. We addressed these challenges by building \supersketch{}, which automatically discharges most subgoals in a single command, and \superfix{}, which programmatically repairs broken proofs when upstream changes occur. Together, they significantly reduced the manual tedium, allowing us to finalize a proof of coherence for a model with nearly 800 conjuncts.

We hope that our account of these methods—and their success in a genuinely large case study—can help other proof engineers build more scalable verification pipelines, and that it motivates further work on integrated proof-maintenance tooling for ITPs.

